<body>
    <h1>Implement the Tweet\Value class</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <div class=3D"contentLayout2">=20
<div class=3D"columnLayout two-right-sidebar" data-layout=3D"two-right-side=
bar">=20
<div class=3D"cell normal" data-type=3D"normal">=20
<div class=3D"innerCell">=20
<p>The Value class of a Field Type is by design very simple. It is meant to=
 be stateless, and as lightweight as possible. Therefore, this class must c=
ontain as little logic as possible, as this is the responsibility of the Ty=
pe class .</p>
<p>The Value will at least contain:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>public properties, used to store the actual data&nbsp;</p></li>
<li><p>an implementation of the <code>__toString()</code> method (required =
by the Value interface we inherit from)</p></li>
</ul>
<p>By default, the constructor from <code> FieldType\Value </code> will be =
used, and allows you to pass a hash of property/value pairs. In our example=
, we can see that we can override it as well if we want.</p>
<p>The Tweet Field Type is going to store three things:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>The tweet=E2=80=99s URL</p></li>
<li><p>The tweet=E2=80=99s author URL</p></li>
<li><p>The body, as an HTML string &nbsp;</p></li>
</ul>
<p>At this point, we don=E2=80=99t care where those are stored. All we care=
 about is what we want our Field Type to expose as an API. We end up with t=
he following properties:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>eZ/FieldType/Tweet/Value.php</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"brush: php; gutter: false; theme: Eclipse" style=3D"font-size=
:12px;">/**
* Tweet URL on twitter.com (http://twitter.com/UserName/status/id).
* @var string
*/
public $url;

=20
/**
* Author's tweet URL (http://twitter.com/UserName)
* @var string
*/
public $authorUrl;

=20
/**
* The tweet's embed HTML
* @var string
*/
public $contents;</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>The only thing left to honor the <code> FieldType\Value </code> interfac=
e is the <code> __toString()</code> method. Let=E2=80=99s say that ours wil=
l return the tweet=E2=80=99s URL:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>eZ/FieldType/Tweet/Value.php</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"brush: php; gutter: false; theme: Eclipse" style=3D"font-size=
:12px;">public function __toString()
{
   return $this-&gt;url;
}</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
</div>=20
</div>=20
